mines the working relationship between the pair and the contribution that Herrmann's work brings to Hitchcock's idiom. Examining key works, including The Man Who Knew Too Much, Psycho, Marnie and Vertigo, the essays explore approaches to sound, music, collaborative authorship and the distinctive contribution that Herrmann's work with Hitchcock brought to this body of films, examining the significance, meanings, histories and enduring legacies of one of film history's most important partnerships. By engaging with the collaborative work of Hitchcock and Herrmann, the book explores the ways in which film directors and composers collaborate, how this collaboration is experienced in the film text, and the ways in which such partnerships inspire later work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and direction. 0aSuspense in motion pictures, television, etc. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAlfred Hitchcock.  aBernard Herrmann.  afilm authorship.  afilm history.  afilm music.  afilm studies.  amusicology.1 aAllen, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Royal S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifton, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, K. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Kevin J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGottlieb, Sidney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc